The name of the Cynics was given them in the time of their founder, Antisthenes, immediately after the death of Socrates, his teacher. But the popular idea of their character is de- rived more from Diogenes of Sinope, the crabbed disciple of Antis· thenes. The Stoic school was founded full three-quartem of a century after the Cynic by Zen0, who had in his earlier studies attached him· sels to the Cynics, but modified his opinione„ and gave to the views of that school a more general and expansive character.
